def vis_1():
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 8))
    bDate= ['11/26', '11/27', '11/28', '11/29', '11/30', '12/1', '12/2', '12/3', '12/4', '12/5', '12/6', '12/7', '12/8', '12/9', '12/10', '12/11', '12/12', '12/13', '12/14', '12/15', '12/16', '12/17', '12/18', '12/19', '12/20', '12/21', '12/22', '12/23', '12/24']
    # Plot data from the files
    plt.plot(bDate, yr_One['TotalSales'], label='2018')
    plt.plot(bDate, yr_Two['TotalSales'], label='2019')
    plt.plot(bDate, yr_Three['TotalSales'], label='2020')
    plt.plot(bDate, yr_Four['TotalSales'], label='2021')
    plt.plot(bDate, yr_Five['TotalSales'], label='2022')

    plt.xlabel('Day')

    plt.title('Sales by Day')
    # Add legend
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Figure 2: Avg Sales By Week Over 5 Years

# All years into a single DataFrame
all_years = pd.concat([yr_One, yr_Two, yr_Three, yr_Four, yr_Five])
# Datetime format
all_years['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(all_years['Date'])
# Set 'Date' as the index
all_years.set_index('Date', inplace=True)
# Calculate week of the month for a given datetime
def week_of_month(dt):
    first_day = dt.replace(day=1)
    # Calculate the number of days between the current date and the first day
    dom = (dt - first_day).days
    # Calculate the adjusted day of the month considering the first day of the month could be any day of the week
    adjusted_dom = dom + first_day.weekday()
    # Return the ceiling of the adjusted day of the month divided by 7
    return int(ceil(adjusted_dom / 7.0))

# Create 'WeekOfMonth' column
all_years['WeekOfMonth'] = all_years.index.to_series().apply(week_of_month)
# Sum of sales for each week of the month
weekly_sales = all_years.groupby('WeekOfMonth')['TotalSales'].sum()
# Find the average sales for each week across the month (over the 5-year period)
average_weekly_sales = weekly_sales.groupby(weekly_sales.index).mean()
# Find the week with the highest average sales
highest_sales_week = average_weekly_sales.idxmax()

weekly_sales_qty = all_years.groupby('WeekOfMonth')['TotalQty'].sum()
# Find the average sales for each week across the month (over the 5-year period)
average_weekly_sales_qty = weekly_sales_qty.groupby(weekly_sales.index).mean()
# Find the week with the highest average sales
highest_sales_qty_week = average_weekly_sales_qty.idxmax()

def vis_3():
    wDate = average_weekly_sales_qty.index.tolist()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.plot(wDate, average_weekly_sales_qty, marker='o', label='Average Sales Qty')
    plt.xlabel('Week of the Month')
    plt.ylabel('Average Total Sales Qty')
    plt.title('Average Weekly Sales Qty Over Five Years')
    plt.xticks(wDate)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    

def vis_2():
    wDate = average_weekly_sales.index.tolist()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.plot(wDate, average_weekly_sales, marker='o', label='Average Sales')
    plt.xlabel('Week of the Month')
    plt.ylabel('Average Total Sales (USD)')
    plt.title('Average Weekly Sales Over Five Years')
    plt.xticks(wDate)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

def reg_test():
    all_years['DayOfWeek'] = all_years.index.dayofweek
    model = ols('TotalSales ~ NobleFirSales + DouglasFirSales + TotalQty + NobleQty + DouglasQty + DayOfWeek', data=all_years).fit()
    print(model.summary())

def login(users):
    print("\nLogin Below:")
    username = input("Enter username: ")
    password = input("Enter password: ")

    if username in users and users[username] == password:
        return True
    else:
        print("Invalid username or password.")
        return login(users), username, password

	Daily total sales amounts over the 5 years generally suggest that the dates 12/6 - 12/13 have the highest daily sales.


	The week with the highest average sales is: Week 2 with sales of $768,010.85

Interestingly, this differs to the daily total sales, but there is a spread of variance between which days saw the highest sales based on the
dates that make up the second and third week year to year. More data should be examined in years to come.


	The week with the highest average sales is: Week 2 with sales quantity of 9,612

Though the pattern generally matches with the average weekly sales, the gap between week 2 and 3 is smaller for average weekly quantity than for
the average weekly sales.

Looking at this, it would seem that the best course of action is to add a $2 premium charge for the 3rd week, to increase profit margins on a
week that experiences a gap between quantity and sales revenue. This will hopefully even out the trends we are seeing.
